1
00:00:00,170 --> 00:00:03,920
In this video we are going to learn what is RabbitMQ?

2
00:00:04,550 --> 00:00:10,340
RabbitMQ is a message broker software that implements the Advanced Messaging Queue protocol, which

3
00:00:10,340 --> 00:00:12,350
is the Amqp protocol.

4
00:00:13,010 --> 00:00:18,620
It allows applications to communicate with each other by sending and receiving messages through the

5
00:00:18,620 --> 00:00:19,220
queues.

6
00:00:19,850 --> 00:00:22,520
So RabbitMQ is a message queuing system.

7
00:00:22,520 --> 00:00:30,980
Similar ones can be listed as a Apache Kafka, Msmq, Microsoft Azure, Service Bus, kestrel, Activemq

8
00:00:30,980 --> 00:00:31,820
and so on.

9
00:00:32,659 --> 00:00:39,260
It is proposed to transmit a message received from any source to another source as soon as it is their

10
00:00:39,260 --> 00:00:39,800
turn.

11
00:00:39,800 --> 00:00:46,670
In other words, all transactions can be listed in a queue until the source to be transmitted gets up.

12
00:00:47,950 --> 00:00:51,460
It also allowed to send and receive messages asynchronously.

13
00:00:51,490 --> 00:00:58,030
This decouples the sender and receiver, allowing each to continue processing without waiting for other

14
00:00:58,030 --> 00:00:58,720
to respond.

15
00:00:58,750 --> 00:01:02,950
This can improve the overall performance and scalability of the system.

16
00:01:03,430 --> 00:01:10,090
RabbitMQ supports for multiple operating systems and open source code in one of the most preferred reasons.

17
00:01:10,480 --> 00:01:18,610
The main components of RabbitMQ are producer queue, consumer message exchange, binding and Fifo.

18
00:01:18,730 --> 00:01:24,160
So I will explain all these components on the RabbitMQ architecture that you can see on the picture.

19
00:01:24,190 --> 00:01:26,470
So let me start with the producer.

20
00:01:26,560 --> 00:01:29,500
I will continue with the producer queue and consumer.

21
00:01:29,500 --> 00:01:32,590
And after that I will explain the exchange and bindings.

22
00:01:32,950 --> 00:01:34,120
So what is producer?

23
00:01:34,150 --> 00:01:37,450
Producer is the source of the message for the application.

24
00:01:37,840 --> 00:01:40,480
So after that what is Q?

25
00:01:40,510 --> 00:01:43,120
Q is where the messages are stored.

26
00:01:43,120 --> 00:01:47,170
The sent messages are put in queue before they are received.

27
00:01:47,170 --> 00:01:49,870
All incoming messages are stored in the queue.

28
00:01:49,900 --> 00:01:51,190
That is the memory.

29
00:01:52,390 --> 00:01:54,370
And after that we have consumer.

30
00:01:54,370 --> 00:01:55,450
It is a server.

31
00:01:55,450 --> 00:01:57,190
That means the send message.

32
00:01:57,190 --> 00:02:01,240
It is the application that will receive and process the message on the queue.

33
00:02:01,780 --> 00:02:03,820
And also we have a message.

34
00:02:03,820 --> 00:02:06,910
Message is the data that we send on the queue.

35
00:02:07,180 --> 00:02:10,449
So now I can explain exchange and bindings.

36
00:02:10,449 --> 00:02:12,220
So what is the exchange.

37
00:02:12,610 --> 00:02:16,810
It is a structure that decides which queue to send the messages.

38
00:02:16,840 --> 00:02:20,350
It makes the decision according to routing case.

39
00:02:21,230 --> 00:02:22,880
And also we have bindings.

40
00:02:22,910 --> 00:02:26,420
Bindings are the link between the exchange and the queues.

41
00:02:27,110 --> 00:02:29,390
And also we can explain the Fifo.

42
00:02:29,420 --> 00:02:30,590
What is the Fifo?

43
00:02:30,620 --> 00:02:34,880
Fifo is the order of processing of outgoing messages in RabbitMQ.

44
00:02:34,910 --> 00:02:35,390
In.

45
00:02:35,390 --> 00:02:35,930
First in.

46
00:02:35,930 --> 00:02:36,650
First out.

